My problem with this is, what if the user lies about the length of their buffer? How can the kernel return ERROR_INSUFFICIENT_BUFFER, rather than trigger an access violation?

last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
>>1286855
>what if the user lies about the length of their buffer?
Then their program crashes. The kernel is handed a pointer into userspace, so it just scribbles userspace without damaging the kernel memory.

last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
>>1286855
To elaborate, Windows puts the kernel memory in one half of the virtual address space, and the process that made the system call's memory in the other half (this is why 32-bit Windows processes can only have 2GB, even if PAE Windows has way more physical memory). So all the kernel has to do to protect itself is to always write to userspace through a statically-validated function that makes sure the entire write takes place in the user-process half of the virtual memory space. This doesn't involve any extra context switches and is therefore "fast". Because of the way x86/x64 protection rings work, the kernel can write to both segments, but the user process cannot. But they can still share the same memory mapping, which keeps the TLB valid (and therefore hot) across the context switch into the kernel.

If you provide a buffer that's too small, but is still in your process's address space, the kernel will write to it anyway, possibly triggering a page fault (that the kernel can handle, because the memory management interrupt handlers are all designed to be able to run in the middle of other kernel calls, including each other (this is called being "reentrant")).
If you provide a pointer to kernel space, you get killed by the scheduler or told your buffer is invalid (I can't remember what Windows actually does, it doesn't really matter because you shouldn't ever see that behaviour anyway).

last_replies.name: Anonymous

>make sure the partitions are 4k-aligned
If you've never partitioned the disk and are just using the computer the way it came, or you reinstalled windows but you didn't use custom settings for the partitions/drive letters, then it will be aligned already and you don't need to worry.
4k alignment is a thing because the disk stores data in 4096 byte chunks, and the OS stores data in 4096 byte chunks, but for historical reasons the way you talk to the disk is with 512 byte chunks, so you can get the on-disk sectors and the filesystem sectors out of alignment, then every time you write a sector the disk needs to read two and write two.
But this isn't something you have to worry about if your computer wasn't upgraded from Windows XP or partitioned manually.

last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
>>1286838
>SATA cable
This is the wire the computer uses to talk to the disk. If you've got a laptop, it's often just a connector on the motherboard. These are difficult/impossible to replace, but also very unlikely to fail. In a desktop, it's an easily-replaced $5 wire.
If the SATA cable works, but not perfectly, this causes packet loss talking to the disk, and the OS can freeze for multiple seconds with "100% activity" but nothing actually happening. To the user, this usually looks like the disk light is on, but the disk isn't making disk noises.
This exact problem can also be caused by a dying transceiver ("PHY") on the disk, in which case replacing the cable won't fix it but replacing the disk will, or a dying PHY on the motherboard*, in which case using a different SATA socket will fix everything.

* which I have never seen, I just mention it as a theoretical possibility

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1unkluyh2Ks
>Pixels
Smallest unit of an image, basically a square of color. When you zoom in on an image in MS Paint, you end up seeing squares. Those are the pixels.
>Resolution
How many pixels you got in an image.
>Height/Width
Since pixels are square, computers like 2D arrays (tables) and cinema film is rectangular, displaying digital images as rectangles has become the standard. Rectangles can be expressed by their height and width. If those are expressed by pixel count, multiplying them gives you the image's resolution. If by length units, it gives you the dimensions of the printed image.
>[Physical] Size
Digital images can be displayed on screens and printed on paper. There is a measure of pixel density named "pixels per inch" (PPI) which is fairly self-explanatory. If you keep your PPI constant and increase your resolution, the physical size of the image grows (you have more of an image). If you keep your resolution constant and increase the PPI, the physical size shrinks (the image becomes denser). If you keep your resolution constant and increase the physical size, the PPI drops and your printed image looks more pixelated (like zooming in in Paint and seeing large pixels).
When doing digital art, physical size matters not. You usually grab a default PPI value like 72 and the program does the conversion on its own. If you're working with prints, then it's important to know the required PPI so you can have the correct resolution for a given size of print.
